<subSubSection id="E17601916747CAA5FF5B885CA14DFA96" pageId="10" pageNumber="41" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="AF84A06914B2F80420316004A6E921EC" pageId="10" pageNumber="41">
<pageBreakToken id="D87481751B4057AA5760BDD6EC3C0B54" pageId="10" pageNumber="41" start="start">Diagnosis</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="421B0C697364F81FF341914BBD78CC4E" pageId="10" pageNumber="41">
The female of this species superficially resembles that of 
<taxonomicName id="6F20B9AF6E51BD74D9B7DF1284DC4D1D" family="Apidae" genus="X." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="X. splendidula" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="splendidula">
<emphasis id="DE6DA886607ECE6AA6808697D9C9C2F5" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="41">X. splendidula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Lepeletier de Saint Fargeau and other small species of 
<taxonomicName id="FA0E35C173A317E82C7C3D27EC1E3286" authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1841" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Schonnherria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" lsidName="Schonnherria" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9BC4417D04643AED52E8BD36C7088040" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="41">Schonnherria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, such as 
<taxonomicName id="8A8B21E2CA3FE2EBAB95E119F81C90B1" family="Apidae" genus="X." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="X. lucida" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="lucida">
<emphasis id="15B34382A8FCC51DD36FDEAE7B305D37" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="41">X. lucida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Smith and 
<taxonomicName id="9851A46CBD8D6B24269C497AA45C2AF3" family="Apidae" genus="X." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="X. muscaria" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="muscaria">
<emphasis id="EAFFE88258B011EFE1F67599A83C1764" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="41">X. muscaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fabricius). However, 
<taxonomicName id="CB087CC533BD80D20585DD4F5611B0D0" family="Apidae" genus="X." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="X. bigibbosa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="bigibbosa">
<emphasis id="41100AB5CD8A2F8E5EB8859346343EAC" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="41">X. bigibbosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily separated from those species and from any other species of the subgenus by the mesoscutum anteriorly with two distinct round tubercles (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D94BF8F963773CA2FCD698F658A29613" captionStart="Figures 12–16" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 12 - 16. Female holotype of Xylocopa (Schonnherria) bigibbosa sp. n. 12 Facial view 13 Lateral habitus 14 Dorsal habitus 15 Detail of mesoscutum in profile with arrow pointing to tubercles 16 Detail of T 1 - T 3." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.61.20345.figures12-16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/174970" pageId="10" pageNumber="41">15</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
